post_text: Important Message for Our Remote Learning Families in Kinder, 1st, 2nd, and 3rd grades. The state of Arizona requires all remote learners to complete reading and math beginning of the year assessments within the first 6 weeks of school. For kinder through 3rd graders, this assessment will be in person at WEMS next week and will take 45 minutes. We've called and arranged appointments with many families already for next Wednesday, Sept. 9th and Thursday, Sept. 10th. If we couldn't reach you or you don't know your appointment time, you need to call the school on Tuesday. Tuesday will be 1st grade (12-2 p.m.) and 2nd grade (2-3:30 p.m.). Wednesday will be 3rd grade (1:30-2:30) and kindergarten (2:30-3:30 p.m.). Siblings in different grades will be grouped together for your convenience. Thank you in advance for bringing your child in and keeping them in good standing with the AZ Department of Education. --Dr. Morrison

post_text:
Greetings Viking Families: as promised, we continue to seek solutions that streamline the WHS online learning environment. Today, I am pleased to roll out 2 very important items to increase the simplicity & efficiency of the online environment.

1. A universal way to take daily attendance:
In Google Classroom, students will go to "Classwork" and then Daily Attendance Topic/Heading. Click on the Google Forms Sign In for that Daily Attendance assignment & click on the one question that states something like "I am here and present for class today". It will send the teacher a date and timestamp of your log in/check in. Do this for every class, every day/time you go into Google Classroom.

2. A master Zoom schedule for online learners .
Please see the link here: https://5il.co/kgnp

Greetings WHS Families: After the release of last night's online schedule for WHS, one big question remains. "How do I know if my child(ren) are in the A or B groups"?

Teachers are creating these flexible groups and will let students know during the first few days of school. If conflicts arise in a schedule, teachers and students can work together to switch in/out of A or B to accommodate.

Creating A and B allows us additional flexibility and balances out the "size" of Zoom meetings/"rooms".

Patience will be key. Communication will be necessary. I thank you in advance for both.

Mr. Evans***

post_text:
To clarify: The school year starts for all WEMS students on August 10th with remote learning from home. Unless the state directs us otherwise, we will transition to on-campus learning for students who selected that option on August 17th. ALL students in grades 3-8 will be issued individual Chromebooks next week (pick-up schedule sent separately). For PreK-2 students, we will have touch-screen devices, but they have not arrived yet. As a result, we will mail PreK-2 work packets to all PreK-2 students' home addresses for that first week of learning (arriving on 8/10 or 8/11). There will also be online opportunities that first week for PreK-2 families with SmartPhones or other devices. Finally, Hotspots will be available for families without Internet access.

Please stay connected to critical school information by downloading our app, visiting our website at www.wusd2.org, or liking us on Facebook. We look forward to serving you to the best of our abilities this year!

Take advantage of our social-distancing registration process by coming to our school's long hallway any Monday through Thursday, 8 a.m. to 2 p.m. There, you'll find registration packets, lunch forms, and more. Fill out the paperwork in the comfort of your own home and then return it to our secure drop-box in the WEMS long hallway by Monday, July 27th. Prefer to print out the paperwork yourself? Just visit our website at www.wusd2.org. Finally, we will hold brief, in-person registration for families who need additional help in late July/early August. We do, however, encourage you to register now and get a head-start on the school year because...it's going to be a great one!

Greetings GRADUATED! Seniors of the Class of 2020!
Congrats! I hope each of you enjoyed our ceremony and that it brought some closure to your time at WHS. We wish each of you the best & brightest of futures. One piece of advice, nothing can replace hard work! Whatever you pursue, be a good, hard worker! You'll be valued anywhere that you go!

Diplomas can be picked up in the front office M-Thur 9-3 pm. All fees must be paid, borrowed graduation regalia returned, and all sports uniforms returned as well.

Be well Class of 2020 and don't be strangers! Come see us when we re-open.

Kind regards,
Your WHS Family

post_text:
Congratulations class of 2020! For upcoming seniors in the class of 2021 I want to remind all who are planning on attending any additional training after they graduate (University, community college, or trade school) that now is the time to start looking for scholarships. While many scholarships may have not opened yet there are some out there already and you should begin to get into a habit and routine of looking and applying. While there are many sites out there that are databases for all scholarships some of my favorite that you should sign up for are Going Merry, FastWeb, Scholarship.com, and StudentScholarships.org. College Board has some oney just for doing what you are going to be doing anyways your senior year. Also look for apps as there are oodles of those too. University, community college, or trade schools can be expensive but if you put in the time you could do these for free! Have a great summer and be safe.
-Mr. Powers

post_text: WHS Message # 2: WHS will have an in-person, voluntary Graduation Ceremony for the Class of 2020 on Friday May 29th @ 7 pm on the WHS Football Field. Seating will be limited to 6 people per graduate, not including the graduate. Guests should be a max of 6 immediate/nuclear family members living in the same household, or a max of 6 immediate/nuclear family members that live in a dual household situation. Dual households will be seated with social distancing from one another. More details to come in our online invitation link that will come out shortly. We know there are going to be questions. Your patience is greatly appreciated. More info will continue to roll out to each of you.

post_text:
Greetings WHS Seniors, the Mighty Class of 2020! This is alert # 1 of several this week re: end of the year information. Save these and I'll number these, to assist us all with this delicate and unusual process.

Friday, May 22nd, at 20:20 pm, we will light the football field/scoreboard for the final time for the Seniors. At 8:30 pm, there will be fireworks! Senior names will be read over the loudspeaker & 3 fireworks will be sent up into the sky for each senior, followed by a 2 minute long Grand Finale. We ask that you help us observe social distancing by staying in your vehicles and/or along the fences and that we park all along W Sheridan Ave, S 9th St., S 7th St., and W Oak St. in a box/square all around the block/school that has a view. Please avoid the baseball field during this time. Thank you!

WHS will announce this year's scholarship winners, Valedictorian/Salutatorian/Historian, and Academic Achievement Awards. The video will remain on these two sites, so watching it "live" is not necessary. Those Seniors receiving a scholarship award will receive a personal phone call invite (to watch the video presentation) from Miss Laci.

-Mr. Evans and the WHS Family-

post_text: It's National Teacher Appreciation Week. At WUSD, we like to celebrate Educator Appreciation Week and recognize the hard work of ALL our staff--teachers, aides, custodians, bus drivers, cafeteria staff, office staff, administrators, and everyone else! Thanks to our incredibly dedicated group of educators for making WUSD a caring place where students and their educations matter most. To start the week off, we'd like to shine a spotlight on our cafeteria staff, a.k.a. The Lunch Bunch! Since the start of the school closure...every day at dawn, these ladies are up and at 'em making wonderful hot meals to send home to students. Thanks, Lunch Bunch, for being such a strong team. And, thanks to all of our WUSD staff for doing what they do and doing it well! Look for more WUSD Educator Spotlights this week!

post_text:
Governor Ducey and DES expand Arizona's commitment to food security for Arizona children. Due to the pandemic, families whose children receive free or reduced lunch at school are now eligible for additional food assistance, retroactive back to March 16, 2020. Eligible families will receive $69 for March, $126 in April, and $120 in May, for each child. To apply for Nutrition Assistance, visit healthearizonaplus.gov or call 1-855-432-7587, 7am-6pm Monday through Friday.

https://azgovernor.gov/governor/news/2020/04/arizona-provide-nearly-600000-children-pandemic-school-meal-replacement?fbclid=IwAR0ksnehJn1j4hvm_WzJ-vcHlRqOF4JxAuRnjgaO7wxbSDYm847Nly6XaYs

post_text: Let's stay connected, WUSD Families! Next week, we're holding a Virtual Spirit Week. Monday is P.J./Crazy Hair Day, in honor of everyone spending more time at home. Tuesday is Super Hero Day, in honor of healthcare professionals, first responders, and other essential workers (like educators!). Wednesday is Selfie with Your Fave Food or Fave Pet Day, in honor of animal care workers and grocery store workers. And, Thursday is Jersey/Team Day, in honor of all student, college, and pro athletes who are unable to play this season. Greetings WHS Families that pick up packet work for WHS students:

When requesting work at WEMS or ANY of our 3 other remote locations, it is imperative that you please tell us:

1. Course Name AND
2. Teacher Name

Multiple teachers teach different courses within the same subject and not all kids are necessarily in a course that is usually reserved for a certain grade.

By doing this, we can get you faster and better service and your child gets exactly what they need.

Thank you for your assistance with this. It will save very valuable time and help us to keep long lines on Mondays moving.

Be Well.

Mr. Evans

post_text: WEMS is partnering with you to ensure your child continues learning during the school closure. New weekly paper learning packets will continue to be available for pick-up at meal sites every Monday. Starting this Thursday, paper packets can be turned in at meal sites every Thursday. Work submitted cannnot hurt a child's 2nd semester grade, but can definitely improve it! So, turn that work in! Online learning continues through Google Classroom and other platforms. Google Classroom access codes vary by teacher and grade, so contact your teacher or the school for more information. Also, every teacher will soon be starting weekly office hours. This could look different depending upon the grade level. It might be a show and tell, an interactive lesson, a science experiment demo, or a Q & A for students and parents on how to do some of that challenging schoolwork! WEMS is "Built to Serve" and we thank you for working with us.

post_text:
Greetings WHS Seniors & Parents/Guardians of WHS Seniors: The last few weeks have presented some very uncertain & uneasy times for folks all over the country & all over the world. Schools, sports seasons & events cancelled all over the world. Public gatherings limited to 10 or less people, 6 feet apart, etc. Certainly anxious times.

During these uncertain times, it is nice once in a while to get some news that is certain.

Our promise to our Senior Class of 2020 is:
At some point, when conditions allow, WHS WILL hold a Commencement/Graduation Ceremony of some kind. We don't know when, or how yet, but our commitment to our Seniors tonight, is that WHS WILL find a way to celebrate this wonderful, lifelong accomplishment.

Stay tuned & Be Well. Our thoughts are with you.

Mr. Evans & the WHS Team***

Greetings WHS Families and Student Athletes:
Please see the message below from the AIA:

Arizona Governor Doug Ducey recently announced that all statewide schools will be closed through Friday, April 10. With this directive, the AIA and its Executive Board must abide by this decision and require that all AIA member schools not partake in interscholastic competition until further notified.
The spring sports championships are still not cancelled at this point. However, discussions for the administration of any postseason tournaments will not take place until after schools are back in session.
The AIA will continue to monitor the communications from the governor‚Äôs office and make decisions accordingly. In the meantime, we want all of our student-athletes, coaches and teachers to stay safe and follow all health department advisories.

post_text: There's lots happening at WEMS this week! Monday: Read Across America Week/Dr. Seuss's Birthday from 2:45-3:45. Students can dress up as their fave Dr. Seuss character or in their P.J.'s for partnered reading and cupcakes! Tuesday: WEMS Annual STEAM Night from 5 to 7 p.m. in the gym. Hands-on science, technology, engineering, art, and math activities, The Arizona Science Center and more! Free to all community members. Finally, Thursday: The PTSA will host a Sock Hop Dance from 5 to 7 p.m. in the cafeteria. Students should bring their mom, dad, or other important adult. $5 per person, $20 max per family, and under 3 are free. See you this week at WEMS!

post_text: Greetings from the WUSD Food Service Department. We want to take a moment to notify you that schools offer a nutritious breakfast starting at 7:30 AM and lunch each school day. The meals are offered according to your child‚Äôs approved meal status. Students can eat free, at a reduced rate, or full price. If you are not sure if your student qualifies for free or reduced meals, please feel free to contact Chris Sanders at any time Monday thru Thursday by calling 1-928-635-4428 ext. 124 or email csanders@wusd2.org. Our lunch ladies have noticed there are some students not eating during the day, so we are reaching out to parents to help us by encouraging their children to eat at school. Studies have found students that eat healthy meals perform better in school. We look forward to serving healthy nutritious meals to all students in accordance with the National School Lunch Programs (NSLP) guidelines. Please visit our Food Service page for meal application and pricing. https://www.wusd2.org/o/wusd/page/food-service--222

post_text: Greetings WHS Families: WUSD & WHS would like to share with you a newer/updated feature to our district website. You can report a bullying incident through our website, straight to your campus administrator. It can be anonymous (if you wish) and it's a simple, short process. From the home screen of the district website, click on "REPORT A BULLYING INCIDENT: help yourself, help others" icon. Definitions are provided to help clarify and best report the type of incident that occurred/is occurring. Thank you!

post_text: This Thursday, WEMS elementary students (K-5) have the opportunity to participate in JumpRope for Heart in their Fit Kids classes. Students do not need to have fundraised in order to participate, but do need to turn in a signed permission slip. Students can pick up an extra permission slip this week so they can participate on Thursday. Our goal: 100% of students jumping rope together on Thursday for heart health!

post_text: Thanks to Williams Alliance for the Arts and Kris Williams especially for sponsoring a visit from photographer and documentary filmmaker Efren Lopez this past week. Mr Lopez held a Q&A session after sharing his documentary with our 8th graders. Very powerful film about his military service in Afghanistan. What a great addition to the Identity through Photography project! You can view the photographs from our students' participation in this project at The Gallery in Williams throughout the month of April.
